    "longDesc": "Delirium due to known physiological condition",
    "plainEnglish": "Delirium is a serious state of confusion where your thinking becomes disorganized, you may be disoriented about time or place, and your attention is scattered—and in this case, doctors have identified a specific medical condition as the cause (such as an infection, medication side effect, organ failure, or electrolyte imbalance). This is different from dementia because it comes on suddenly and can potentially improve once the underlying medical problem is treated. You might experience rapid mood changes, difficulty concentrating, sleep disturbances, or hallucinations.",
    "whoUses": "Internists, hospitalists, emergency medicine doctors, and intensivists commonly use this code when treating hospitalized or critically ill patients who develop acute confusion from a treatable medical cause. It frequently appears on hospital bills and EOBs for inpatient stays, particularly in ICU or acute care settings.",
