    "shortDesc": "Mood disorder due to known physiol cond w manic features",
    "longDesc": "Mood disorder due to known physiological condition with manic features",
    "plainEnglish": "This diagnosis means you're experiencing manic symptoms—such as unusually elevated mood, increased energy, racing thoughts, or impulsive behavior—that are directly caused by a medical condition affecting your brain or body rather than by a primary psychiatric disorder. Examples might include mania triggered by a thyroid problem, neurological condition, medication side effect, or another treatable medical issue. Unlike bipolar disorder, which is a primary psychiatric condition, your mood changes have an identifiable physical cause that your doctor can investigate and potentially treat.",
    "whoUses": "Psychiatrists, neurologists, internists, and primary care doctors use this code when they've identified that a patient's manic symptoms stem from an underlying medical condition rather than a psychiatric illness. It commonly appears on EOB statements for patients receiving psychiatric or medical workup to determine the root cause of their mood symptoms, and helps justify further diagnostic testing or specialist referrals.",
