    "plainEnglish": "This code describes a serious condition where someone who has been drinking alcohol heavily stops or reduces their drinking, and their body reacts with confusion, hallucinations, and agitation—a state called delirium. Alcohol withdrawal delirium (also known as delirium tremens or DTs) happens because the brain has become dependent on alcohol, and when the drug is suddenly removed, the nervous system becomes dangerously overactive. Patients experiencing this may see or hear things that aren't real, feel extremely anxious or paranoid, and have trouble thinking clearly.",
    "whoUses": "Emergency medicine physicians, addiction medicine specialists, intensivists, and psychiatrists use this code when treating patients in acute withdrawal in hospital or emergency settings. It commonly appears on EOB statements for patients hospitalized or seen in the ER for severe alcohol withdrawal complications, as this is a medical emergency requiring intensive monitoring and treatment.",
