    "longDesc": "Opioid abuse, uncomplicated",
    "plainEnglish": "This code indicates that you are using opioid medications (such as heroin, prescription painkillers, or other opioid drugs) in a way that is harmful to your health, but without serious complications like overdose or infection at this time. Opioid abuse means taking these drugs more frequently or in higher doses than prescribed, or using them for reasons other than medical treatment—which can lead to dependence, overdose, and other serious health problems.",
    "whoUses": "This code is commonly used by addiction medicine specialists, primary care doctors, psychiatrists, and emergency medicine physicians when documenting substance use disorders in patients. It frequently appears on EOB statements for patients seeking treatment at addiction clinics, mental health facilities, or emergency departments, and is important for insurance coverage of counseling and rehabilitation services.",
