    "rawCode": "F11120",
    "shortDesc": "Opioid abuse with intoxication, uncomplicated",
    "longDesc": "Opioid abuse with intoxication, uncomplicated",
    "plainEnglish": "This code indicates that a person is misusing opioid medications or drugs (like heroin, prescription painkillers, or other opioids) and is currently experiencing intoxication from them—meaning the drug is actively in their system affecting their body and mind. 'Uncomplicated' means there are no serious immediate medical emergencies happening right now, though opioid intoxication can still cause drowsiness, confusion, slowed breathing, and impaired judgment.",
    "whoUses": "Addiction medicine specialists, emergency department physicians, psychiatrists, and primary care doctors use this code when treating patients with opioid misuse disorders. It commonly appears on EOB statements for emergency room visits, urgent care evaluations, or addiction treatment encounters where a patient presents with active opioid intoxication.",
