    "longDesc": "Opioid abuse with intoxication with perceptual disturbance",
    "plainEnglish": "This code indicates that someone is abusing opioid medications or drugs (like heroin, prescription painkillers, or other opioid substances) and is currently experiencing intoxication—meaning the drug is in their system and affecting how their body and mind are functioning. The \"perceptual disturbance\" part means they're having altered sensations or seeing, hearing, or perceiving things in a distorted way, which can happen when opioids are being misused at higher doses. This is different from simple pain relief; it reflects a pattern of using opioids in a harmful way that's causing noticeable changes in how they sense their surroundings.",
    "whoUses": "This code is used by emergency medicine physicians, addiction medicine specialists, psychiatrists, and substance abuse counselors when treating patients who present with active opioid intoxication and associated hallucinations or perceptual changes. It commonly appears on EOB statements for emergency department visits, inpatient psychiatric admissions, or addiction treatment programs, and helps document the severity and specific nature of the opioid misuse for clinical and billing purposes.",
