    "shortDesc": "Opioid abuse with withdrawal",
    "longDesc": "Opioid abuse with withdrawal",
    "plainEnglish": "This code describes a pattern of misusing opioid medications (like prescription painkillers or heroin) combined with experiencing withdrawal symptoms when the person stops using or reduces their dose. Withdrawal from opioids causes uncomfortable physical and mental symptoms such as muscle aches, anxiety, sweating, nausea, and intense cravings, which can occur within hours to days of last use. This diagnosis indicates the person has both a problematic relationship with opioids and is currently dealing with the body's reaction to stopping or cutting back.",
    "whoUses": "Addiction medicine specialists, psychiatrists, primary care physicians, and emergency department doctors use this code when treating patients with opioid use disorder who are experiencing withdrawal symptoms. It commonly appears in clinical settings during detoxification, in emergency departments, and in addiction treatment programs, and may appear on patient EOBs related to inpatient hospitalization or specialized addiction treatment services.",
