    "plainEnglish": "This code indicates that you have had an addiction to opioid medications or drugs (like heroin, prescription painkillers, or fentanyl), but you are currently in remission—meaning you've stopped using and are no longer actively struggling with the addiction. Remission can occur whether you're taking medication-assisted treatment (like methadone or buprenorphine), participating in a recovery program, or have achieved abstinence on your own, and it typically means you haven't used opioids or engaged in problematic opioid-seeking behavior for a defined period.",
    "whoUses": "This code is used by addiction medicine specialists, psychiatrists, primary care physicians, and pain management doctors when treating patients in recovery from opioid use disorder. It commonly appears on EOB statements when patients are receiving ongoing treatment, counseling, or medication-assisted therapy to maintain their recovery.",
