    "longDesc": "Opioid dependence with unspecified opioid-induced disorder",
    "plainEnglish": "This code indicates that a person is dependent on opioids (narcotic pain medications like codeine, morphine, heroin, or prescription painkillers) and is experiencing some kind of opioid-related health problem, but the specific problem hasn't been identified or documented in detail. Opioid dependence means the body and brain have adapted to regular opioid use, so the person experiences withdrawal symptoms or cravings when they try to stop. The 'unspecified disorder' part means there's a medical complication from the opioid use, but the doctor hasn't pinpointed exactly what it is—it could be anything from mood changes to sleep problems to other opioid-related effects.",
    "whoUses": "This code is used by addiction medicine specialists, psychiatrists, primary care physicians, and pain management doctors when treating patients with opioid use disorder who have complications but the specific complication hasn't been clearly identified yet. It commonly appears on EOB statements for patients receiving treatment at addiction clinics, mental health facilities, or during hospitalization for substance use issues.",
