    "plainEnglish": "This code describes someone who uses cannabis (marijuana) and is currently experiencing delirium—a state of confusion, disorientation, and altered awareness—as a direct result of cannabis intoxication. Delirium from cannabis is more serious than typical impairment; it means the person is significantly confused, may not know where they are or what time it is, and might be seeing or hearing things that aren't real. This typically happens when someone has consumed a large amount of cannabis, especially high-potency products.",
    "whoUses": "Psychiatrists, addiction medicine specialists, emergency room physicians, and mental health providers use this code when evaluating patients presenting with acute confusion or altered mental status related to cannabis use. It appears on EOBs when a patient receives emergency or inpatient psychiatric care for cannabis-induced delirium, though it's less common on outpatient bills unless the visit specifically addresses this acute psychiatric symptom.",
